            "response_id": "resp_0eecf96aeae55c0b0069a8c654715c8190ab9e3cfe82191ef0",
            "role": "assistant",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "Kubernetes (often shortened to “K8s”) is an open-source system for **orchestrating containers** (deploying, scaling, and managing containerized applications). Its history is closely tied to Google’s long experience running large-scale production workloads.\n\n- **Google’s internal roots (2000s–early 2010s):** Kubernetes was inspired by Google’s internal cluster-management systems—especially **Borg** (and lessons from related efforts like Omega). These systems automated scheduling and management of large fleets of services across clusters.\n\n- **Project created and open-sourced (2014):** Google began Kubernetes as a new, open project to bring those ideas to the wider industry, designed around containers (especially Docker at the time). Kubernetes was **announced and open-sourced in 2014**, with early contributions from Google and a growing community.\n\n- **Industry stewardship via CNCF (2015):** In 2015, Google helped form the **Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF)** and **donated Kubernetes** to it, establishing neutral governance to encourage broad vendor and community adoption.\n\n- **First stable milestone (2015 onward):** Kubernetes reached **v1.0 in 2015**, signaling a more stable, production-oriented platform. From there, it rapidly expanded its capabilities (networking, storage, security primitives, extensibility).\n\n- **Ecosystem growth and standardization (late 2010s–present):** Kubernetes became the de facto standard for container orchestration, powering managed offerings across cloud providers and enabling a broad “cloud native” ecosystem (e.g., service meshes, operators, GitOps tooling). The project has continued evolving through regular releases under CNCF governance.\n\nIf you tell me whether you want a **high-level narrative** or a **timeline with key release/feature milestones**, I can tailor the summary.",
